associations.evidence_text: TP53 is a well-established tumor suppressor gene that is frequently mutated in lung cancer, contributing to disease development and progression.
EGFR mutations are common in lung adenocarcinoma and are associated with sensitivity to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies.
KRAS mutations are also frequently observed in lung adenocarcinoma and are associated with poorer prognosis and resistance to certain targeted therapies.
ALK rearrangements are found in a subset of lung adenocarcinomas and are targetable by ALK inhibitor drugs.
ERCC1 expression has been associated with resistance to platinum-based chemotherapy in lung cancer, though its role is still under investigation.
BRCA1 mutations have been linked to a small subset of lung cancers, particularly in individuals with a family history of the disease.
BRCA2 mutations have also been reported in lung cancer, though less frequently than BRCA1, and may confer increased sensitivity to certain therapies.
TP53 is a well-established tumor suppressor gene that is frequently mutated in breast cancer, contributing to disease development and progression.
BRCA1 and BRCA2 are known breast cancer susceptibility genes, and germline mutations in these genes are associated with increased risk of developing breast cancer.
BRCA1 and BRCA2 are known breast cancer susceptibility genes, and germline mutations in these genes are associated with increased risk of developing breast cancer.
HER2 (ERBB2) is a well-known oncogene that is amplified or overexpressed in a subset of breast cancers, leading to more aggressive disease and poorer prognosis.
ESR1 (estrogen receptor alpha) is a key driver of hormone-dependent breast cancers, and its expression status is a critical biomarker for treatment selection.
PIK3CA is frequently mutated in breast cancer, leading to activation of the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway and contributing to tumor growth and survival.
PTEN is a tumor suppressor gene that is often inactivated in breast cancer, leading to dysregulation of the PI3K/AKT pathway and promoting tumor progression.
MYC is a proto-oncogene that is frequently amplified or overexpressed in breast cancer, contributing to uncontrolled cell proliferation and tumor growth.
CCND1 (cyclin D1) is a cell cycle regulator that is often amplified or overexpressed in breast cancer, leading to dysregulation of cell cycle control and tumor progression.
TP53 is a well-established tumor suppressor gene that is frequently mutated in colorectal cancer, contributing to disease development and progression.
KRAS mutations are found in a significant proportion of colorectal cancers and are associated with resistance to certain targeted therapies.
APC is a key regulator of the Wnt signaling pathway, and its inactivation is an early and critical event in the development of most colorectal cancers.
BRAF mutations, particularly the V600E mutation, are found in a subset of colorectal cancers and are associated with a more aggressive disease course.
PIK3CA mutations are found in a significant proportion of colorectal cancers and are associated with increased cell proliferation and survival.
PTEN is a tumor suppressor gene that is frequently inactivated in colorectal cancer, leading to dysregulation of the PI3K/Akt signaling pathway.
MYC is a proto-oncogene that is often overexpressed in colorectal cancer, contributing to increased cell proliferation and survival.
CCND1 (cyclin D1) is a cell cycle regulator that is frequently overexpressed in colorectal cancer, leading to uncontrolled cell division.
TP53 is a well-established tumor suppressor gene that is frequently mutated in prostate cancer, contributing to disease progression and aggressiveness.
BRCA1 and BRCA2 germline mutations are known to increase the risk of prostate cancer, especially in younger men.
BRCA1 and BRCA2 germline mutations are known to increase the risk of prostate cancer, especially in younger men.
PTEN is a tumor suppressor gene that is frequently inactivated in prostate cancer, leading to increased cell proliferation and survival.
MYC is a proto-oncogene that is often amplified or overexpressed in prostate cancer, contributing to disease progression and aggressiveness.
CCND1 is a cell cycle regulator that is frequently dysregulated in prostate cancer, leading to uncontrolled cell proliferation.
TP53 is a well-established tumor suppressor gene that is frequently mutated in leukemia, contributing to disease development and progression.
BRCA1 has been implicated in the development of certain types of leukemia, particularly acute myeloid leukemia (AML), through its role in DNA repair and genomic stability.
BRCA2 mutations have been associated with an increased risk of developing certain types of leukemia, such as chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), due to its involvement in DNA repair processes.
MYC is a proto-oncogene that is frequently overexpressed or deregulated in various types of leukemia, contributing to uncontrolled cell growth and proliferation.
CCND1 (Cyclin D1) is a cell cycle regulator that has been found to be overexpressed in certain leukemia subtypes, such as mantle cell lymphoma, and is associated with disease progression.
TP53 mutations are associated with increased risk of ischemic heart disease and myocardial infarction.
PTEN regulates cellular processes involved in ischemic heart disease, including cell growth, proliferation, and apoptosis.
Overexpression of MYC is linked to cardiac hypertrophy and increased risk of ischemic heart disease.
TP53 mutations have been linked to increased risk of ischemic stroke and poorer outcomes.
PTEN regulates cell growth and survival pathways, and its dysregulation has been implicated in stroke pathogenesis.
The PI3K/AKT pathway regulated by PIK3CA plays a key role in neuronal survival and recovery after stroke.
PTEN gene mutations and altered PTEN expression have been linked to the development and progression of hypertension.
Estrogen receptor (ESR1) signaling has been implicated in the regulation of blood pressure and the development of hypertension.
Mutations in the PIK3CA gene have been associated with increased risk of hypertension, likely through its role in regulating vascular function.

PTEN is a tumor suppressor gene that plays a key role in insulin signaling and glucose metabolism. Reduced PTEN expression is associated with insulin resistance and the development of type 2 diabetes.
The PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway regulated by PIK3CA is central to insulin signaling and glucose homeostasis. Dysregulation of this pathway is implicated in the pathogenesis of type 2 diabetes.
CCND1 is involved in cell cycle regulation and its overexpression is associated with insulin resistance and the development of type 2 diabetes.
MYC is a transcription factor that regulates genes involved in glucose metabolism. Altered MYC expression has been linked to impaired insulin sensitivity and glucose homeostasis in type 2 diabetes.
Obesity is associated with increased activation of the PI3K/AKT pathway, which is regulated by the PIK3CA gene.
Obesity is linked to dysregulation of the PTEN tumor suppressor, which negatively regulates the PI3K/AKT pathway.
The MYC oncogene is upregulated in obesity and contributes to adipogenesis and metabolic dysregulation.
The CCND1 gene, which regulates cell cycle progression, is overexpressed in obesity and associated with increased adipogenesis.
PTEN is a tumor suppressor gene that plays a role in insulin signaling and glucose metabolism. Decreased PTEN expression has been linked to the development of metabolic syndrome.
PIK3CA is involved in insulin signaling and glucose homeostasis. Mutations in PIK3CA have been associated with increased risk of metabolic syndrome.
MYC is a transcription factor that regulates cell growth and metabolism. Overexpression of MYC has been linked to the development of metabolic syndrome.
CCND1 is a cell cycle regulator that plays a role in insulin signaling and glucose metabolism. Alterations in CCND1 have been associated with metabolic syndrome.
Increased expression of TP53 has been observed in the brains of Alzheimer's disease patients, suggesting a potential role in the disease pathogenesis.
Alterations in the PTEN gene and protein have been linked to the development of Alzheimer's disease, potentially through its involvement in neuronal signaling and synaptic function.
Increased expression of the MYC proto-oncogene has been observed in Alzheimer's disease, and it may contribute to neuroinflammation and neurodegeneration.
Genetic and functional studies have linked PTEN to the pathogenesis of Parkinson's disease.
Altered expression of the MYC proto-oncogene has been observed in Parkinson's disease brains.
Mutations in TP53 have been linked to increased risk and progression of ALS.
Alterations in PTEN signaling have been implicated in the pathogenesis of ALS.
TP53 has been implicated in the pathogenesis of Huntington's disease, with altered TP53 signaling contributing to neurodegeneration.
BRCA1 has been shown to interact with huntingtin protein and may play a role in the DNA damage response in Huntington's disease.
BRCA2 has also been linked to Huntington's disease, with potential involvement in the DNA damage response and transcriptional regulation.
MYC is a key transcription factor dysregulated in Huntington's disease, contributing to altered gene expression and neurodegeneration.
Estrogen receptor (ESR1) signaling plays a key role in the pathogenesis of rheumatoid arthritis by regulating inflammatory processes and joint destruction.
PTEN, a tumor suppressor, has been implicated in the regulation of inflammatory responses and joint damage in rheumatoid arthritis.
Genetic studies have found associations between BRCA1 mutations and increased risk of systemic lupus erythematosus.
Some research has linked BRCA2 mutations to an elevated risk of developing systemic lupus erythematosus.
Estrogen receptor (ESR1) signaling has been implicated in the pathogenesis of systemic lupus erythematosus, with estrogen playing a role in disease development and progression.
Multiple studies have found that genetic variants and dysregulation of the PTEN tumor suppressor are associated with an increased risk of systemic lupus erythematosus.
PTEN is a tumor suppressor gene that has been implicated in the pathogenesis of multiple sclerosis. Reduced PTEN expression has been observed in brain lesions of multiple sclerosis patients.
Estrogen receptor alpha (ESR1) has been associated with susceptibility to multiple sclerosis. Genetic variants in ESR1 have been linked to disease risk and progression.
Mutations in the APC gene have been strongly linked to the development of Crohn's disease.
Alterations in the PTEN gene have been associated with increased risk of Crohn's disease.
TP53 mutations have been linked to increased risk and severity of psoriasis in multiple studies.
KRAS activation has been observed in psoriatic skin lesions and may contribute to disease pathogenesis.
Overexpression of the MYC proto-oncogene is a hallmark of psoriatic skin and drives keratinocyte proliferation.
Cyclin D1 (CCND1) is a key regulator of cell cycle progression that is upregulated in psoriatic lesions.
TP53 is a tumor suppressor gene that is frequently mutated in HIV-associated cancers, such as Kaposi's sarcoma and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
The MYC oncogene is upregulated in HIV-associated cancers and plays a role in disease progression.
CCND1, a cell cycle regulator, is overexpressed in HIV-associated malignancies and contributes to uncontrolled cell growth.
TP53 mutations have been associated with increased risk of viral hepatitis and liver cancer progression.
Overexpression of MYC has been linked to the development and progression of viral hepatitis-related liver diseases.
Dysregulation of CCND1 (cyclin D1) has been observed in viral hepatitis-induced liver carcinogenesis.
ERCC1 is involved in DNA repair and has been associated with susceptibility to tuberculosis infection and disease progression.
PTEN regulates immune cell function and has been linked to increased risk of tuberculosis in genetic studies.
Malaria infection has been shown to induce MYC expression, which can contribute to disease pathogenesis.
TP53 mutations have been associated with increased susceptibility to severe malaria, though the mechanisms are not fully understood.
ERCC1 is involved in DNA repair and has been associated with COPD pathogenesis and severity.
PTEN plays a role in regulating cell growth and apoptosis, and its dysregulation has been linked to COPD.
Some studies have found associations between EGFR and asthma, but the relationship is not fully understood.
Genetic variations in PTEN have been linked to increased risk of asthma in certain populations.
TP53 mutations have been linked to the development and progression of pulmonary fibrosis.
EGFR signaling has been implicated in the pathogenesis of pulmonary fibrosis, with EGFR inhibitors showing potential therapeutic effects.
PTEN dysregulation has been observed in pulmonary fibrosis, contributing to aberrant cell signaling and fibroblast activation.
PTEN gene mutations are associated with the development and progression of chronic kidney disease.
TP53 gene variants have been linked to increased risk and severity of chronic kidney disease.
KRAS mutations are observed in some forms of chronic kidney disease and may contribute to disease progression.
PIK3CA signaling pathway dysregulation is implicated in the pathogenesis of chronic kidney disease.
PTEN mutations have been linked to the development of nephrotic syndrome through disruption of podocyte function.
TP53 gene variants have been associated with increased risk of nephrotic syndrome, particularly in children.
TP53 mutations are frequently observed in cirrhosis and are associated with disease progression and development of hepatocellular carcinoma.
PTEN inactivation has been linked to cirrhosis and increased risk of hepatocellular carcinoma in cirrhotic patients.
ERCC1 is involved in DNA repair and has been associated with hepatitis-related liver cancer development.
PTEN is a tumor suppressor gene that has been linked to the development of hepatocellular carcinoma, a type of liver cancer associated with hepatitis.
MYC is an oncogene that is frequently overexpressed in hepatocellular carcinoma, which is often caused by chronic hepatitis infection.
CCND1 is a cell cycle regulator that has been implicated in the development of hepatocellular carcinoma associated with chronic hepatitis.
PTEN is involved in regulating lipid metabolism and its dysregulation has been linked to the development of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease.
MYC overexpression has been observed in animal models and human studies of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, suggesting a role in disease pathogenesis.
CCND1, a cell cycle regulator, has been found to be upregulated in non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, contributing to hepatocyte proliferation and disease progression.
Estrogen receptor 1 (ESR1) has been implicated in the pathogenesis of major depressive disorder through its role in regulating mood and emotion-related neural circuits.
PTEN has been linked to major depressive disorder due to its involvement in the regulation of neuronal signaling pathways and synaptic function, which are disrupted in depression.
MYC has been associated with major depressive disorder, as it plays a role in the regulation of neurogenesis and synaptic plasticity, processes that are impaired in depression.
Genetic studies have found associations between TP53 variants and increased risk of schizophrenia.
Altered PTEN signaling has been implicated in the pathogenesis of schizophrenia.
Dysregulation of MYC has been linked to the development of schizophrenia in multiple studies.
PTEN gene variants have been associated with increased risk of bipolar disorder in multiple studies.
Increased expression of the MYC gene has been linked to the development of bipolar disorder.
Genetic variations in the CCND1 gene have been implicated in the pathogenesis of bipolar disorder.
TP53 mutations have been associated with more severe lung disease in cystic fibrosis patients.
Reduced ERCC1 expression has been linked to increased susceptibility to lung infections in cystic fibrosis.
BRCA1 variants may modify the severity of cystic fibrosis lung disease.
BRCA2 mutations have been associated with increased risk of cystic fibrosis-related diabetes.
TP53 mutations have been reported in some cases of Fibrodysplasia Ossificans Progressiva, suggesting a potential role in the disease pathogenesis.
Increased EGFR expression has been observed in Fibrodysplasia Ossificans Progressiva lesions, indicating a possible involvement in the disease process.
Rare cases of Fibrodysplasia Ossificans Progressiva have been reported in individuals with BRCA1 mutations, suggesting a potential genetic link.
Similar to BRCA1, BRCA2 mutations have been observed in a small number of Fibrodysplasia Ossificans Progressiva cases, indicating a possible genetic association.
TP53 mutations have been reported in some cases of neurofibromatosis, suggesting a potential role in the disease pathogenesis.
BRCA1 has been implicated in the development of certain types of neurofibromas, though the relationship is not fully established.
BRCA2 mutations have been associated with increased risk of developing neurofibromas in some studies.
PTEN is a well-established tumor suppressor gene that is frequently mutated in neurofibromatosis type 2, contributing to the development of tumors.
